excerpt: Opened in 1869, this gourmet haunt has 80+ vendors selling organic fruit, premium meats & more.
detail_description: Adelaide Central Market, established in 1869, is a food lover's paradise with over 80 vendors offering organic fruits, premium meats, and more. It is renowned as Adelaide's food hub and one of Australia's largest fresh produce markets. The market features a diverse range of products including fruit and vegetable shops, patisseries, cafes, gourmet cheeses, sweets, and charcuterie. Visitors can enjoy live music on Fridays and participate in various events such as cooking classes and workshops.
name: Adelaide Central Market

excerpt: Modernised 53,500-capacity sports & big-name gig venue, also hosting stadium tours & functions.
detail_description: Adelaide Oval is a modernized sports and entertainment venue with a capacity of 53,500. The stadium's distinctive horseshoe shape and unique roof design make it an iconic landmark. Following restoration, the stadium now hosts a variety of national and international sports events, as well as concerts and functions. The restoration aimed to preserve heritage elements while incorporating modern materials that complement the city's architecture.
name: Adelaide Oval
address: War Memorial Dr, North Adelaide SA 5006, Australia

excerpt: Verdant, 125-acre garden with rare plants like the Wollemi pine, plus statuary, greenhouses & cafes.
detail_description: Adelaide Botanic Garden is a sprawling 125-acre oasis featuring rare plants such as the Wollemi pine and various sculptures, greenhouses, and cafes. The garden offers a range of activities for kids, including meandering pathways, diverse landscapes to explore, birdwatching opportunities, and historic buildings to visit. Visitors can access the garden from multiple entry points and enjoy attractions like the Bicentennial Conservatory - the largest single-span glasshouse in the Southern Hemisphere.
name: Adelaide Botanic Garden

excerpt: 19th-century gallery housing diverse collections with Australian art & important Indigenous works.
detail_description: Nestled in the vibrant cultural precinct of North Terrace, the Art Gallery of South Australia (AGSA) is a treasure trove for art enthusiasts. Established in 1881, this stunning gallery boasts an impressive collection of over 38,000 artworks that span various mediums including painting, sculpture, textiles, and more. A highlight is its extensive array of Indigenous Australian art alongside significant pieces from the colonial era.
name: Art Gallery of South Australia

excerpt: The 5-floor building is devoted to natural history artifacts & an exploration of Aboriginal culture.
detail_description: Nestled on North Terrace, the South Australian Museum is a treasure trove of natural history and Aboriginal culture. This impressive five-story institution houses over four million artifacts, making it a must-visit for anyone interested in Australia’s rich heritage. The museum's extensive collection spans various fields such as biological sciences, archaeology, mineral sciences, and paleontology. Visitors can marvel at everything from taxidermy displays to ancient Egyptian mummies and even dinosaurs!
name: South Australian Museum

excerpt: Bayside Glenelg draws families to its long, sandy beach and the Beachouse amusement centre, with waterslides, rides and arcade games. The Bay Discovery Centre in the 1870s Town Hall has local history exhibits including a vintage swimwear collection, and dolphin-spotting cruises cast off from nearby Holdfast Marina. Laid-back pubs, organic cafes, global eateries and indie boutiques give the area a trendy vibe.
detail_description: Glenelg, a bustling seaside suburb just 11 km from Adelaide city center, is a popular destination known for its long sandy beach and vibrant entertainment options. Families are drawn to the Beachouse amusement center with waterslides and arcade games, while history enthusiasts can explore the Bay Discovery Centre's local exhibits. The area offers a trendy vibe with laid-back pubs, organic cafes, global eateries, and indie boutiques.
name: Glenelg

excerpt: Expansive car-free mall, home to well-known stores & global brands, plus eateries & entertainment.
detail_description: Rundle Mall is a bustling car-free shopping destination in the heart of the city, featuring an impressive array of over 1000 retailers and service providers. It houses major department stores like David Jones and Myer, as well as flagship outlets for renowned global brands such as Apple, H&M, Sephora, and more. The mall also boasts exclusive fashion labels and unique retailers within its various shopping arcades and centers.
name: Rundle Mall

excerpt: Established zoo in a green oasis with thousands of animals, also offering interactive experiences.
detail_description: Adelaide Zoo, nestled in the heart of Adelaide, is a vibrant oasis boasting over 2,500 animals from around the world. Visitors can interact with the wildlife and enjoy unique experiences such as hand-feeding giraffes and observing Giant Pandas Wang Wang and Fu Ni. The zoo offers educational opportunities for all ages and is renowned for its captivating animal collection. As one of Adelaide's top family-friendly attractions, it provides an unforgettable day out for animal lovers.
name: Adelaide Zoo
address: Plane Tree Dr, Adelaide SA 5000, Australia

excerpt: Social history museum displaying exhibits on South Australia's diverse cultures & communities.
detail_description: The Migration Museum in Adelaide, South Australia, offers a captivating exploration of the state's rich cultural tapestry shaped by waves of immigration. Since its establishment in 1986, the museum has curated an extensive collection of artifacts, photographs, and narratives that chronicle the settlement history. It proudly celebrates Adelaide's multiculturalism while fostering respect for diverse cultures and languages. The museum also hosts educational programs and interactive activities for visitors to engage with the exhibits.
name: Migration Museum

excerpt: Hahndorf is a small town in South Australia. Settled by 19th-century Lutheran migrants, it’s known for its original German-style architecture and artisanal food. Hahndorf Academy is home to the German Migration Museum, tracing local history. North of town, the Cedars houses the studio and art of German-born landscape painter Sir Hans Heysen. Numerous wineries in the nearby Adelaide Hills offer tours and tastings.
detail_description: Hahndorf, a charming town in South Australia, was founded by Lutheran migrants in the 19th century. The town is renowned for its original German-style architecture and delectable artisanal food. Visitors can explore the local history at the German Migration Museum housed within Hahndorf Academy. Art enthusiasts can visit the Cedars to admire the studio and art of Sir Hans Heysen, a German-born landscape painter.
name: Hahndorf

detail_description: The State Library of South Australia is a haven for book lovers, offering a serene atmosphere and an extensive collection of leather-bound books housed in the magnificent Mortlock Wing. This mid-Victorian masterpiece features masonry columns, wrought-iron balconies, and a glass-domed roof. The library is not only renowned for its beautiful architecture but also hosts permanent exhibitions showcasing sculptures, artworks, and Indigenous craft rugs.
name: State Library of South Australia

excerpt: Zoo with natural-habitat enclosures, plus hands-on koala & reptile experiences & guided night walks.
detail_description: Cleland Wildlife Park is a 35-hectare lush bushland paradise that serves as a haven for iconic Australian animals. It houses over 130 native species, including kangaroos, reptiles, wombats, and birds in natural-habitat enclosures. Visitors can enjoy hands-on experiences such as holding a koala, hand-feeding kangaroos, or patting a wombat.
name: Cleland Wildlife Park
address: 365 Mount Lofty Summit Rd, Crafers SA 5152, Australia

excerpt: One of the country's longest continuously operating prisons, with history & ghost tours & a museum.
detail_description: Adelaide Gaol, one of the oldest buildings in South Australia, has a rich and eerie history with around 300,000 prisoners once confined within its walls. The gaol offers ghost tours and paranormal workshops for those seeking a spine-chilling experience. Visitors can explore the cells and imagine life for the inmates who once resided there. Additionally, the Migration Museum provides an educational journey through Adelaide's multicultural past, showcasing artifacts, photos, and stories that explain how the state was settled.
name: Adelaide Gaol

excerpt: Museum dedicated to Aboriginal & Torres Strait Islander art & culture, with frequent events.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Adelaide, the Tandanya National Aboriginal Cultural Institute stands as a vibrant testament to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander art and culture. Established in 1989, it proudly holds the title of Australia's oldest Indigenous-owned cultural center. The name "Tandanya," derived from the Kaurna language meaning "place of the red kangaroo," reflects its deep-rooted connection to local heritage.
name: Tandanya (Aboriginal Cultural Institute)
types: Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander organisation

excerpt: Traditional Japanese garden offering meditative paths, an ornamental gate, a lake & a teahouse.
detail_description: The Adelaide Himeji Garden is a peaceful retreat in South Australia's capital, designed to reflect traditional Japanese aesthetics. Established in 1985 as a symbol of the sister city relationship between Adelaide and Himeji, Japan, this serene oasis features elements such as waterfalls, stone lanterns, and meandering pathways that invite visitors to immerse themselves in the tranquility of Japanese landscape architecture.
name: Adelaide Himeji Garden
address: Cnr South Terrace &, Glen Osmond Rd, Adelaide SA 5000, Australia

excerpt: Adelaide is South Australia’s cosmopolitan coastal capital. Its ring of parkland on the River Torrens is home to renowned museums such as the Art Gallery of South Australia, displaying expansive collections including noted Indigenous art, and the South Australian Museum, devoted to natural history. The city's Adelaide Festival is an annual international arts gathering with spin-offs including fringe and film events.
detail_description: Adelaide, the cosmopolitan coastal capital of South Australia, boasts a ring of parkland along the River Torrens and is home to renowned museums like the Art Gallery of South Australia and the South Australian Museum. The city hosts the annual Adelaide Festival, an international arts gathering with fringe and film events.
name: Adelaide

detail_description: Victoria Square, also known as Tarndanyangga, is a bustling town plaza situated at the heart of Adelaide. It is surrounded by various buildings and public institutions such as the Supreme Court of South Australia. The square features a prominent statue of Queen Victoria at its center, making it a popular attraction for tourists visiting Adelaide.
name: Victoria Square

excerpt: Waterfall Gully is an eastern suburb of the South Australian capital city of Adelaide. It is located in the foothills of the Mount Lofty Ranges around 5 km east-south-east of the Adelaide city centre. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Waterfall Gully is an idyllic suburb located in the eastern foothills of the Mount Lofty Ranges, just a short distance from Adelaide's city center. This picturesque area is home to Cleland Conservation Park, where visitors can explore Cleland Wildlife Park, Mount Lofty Summit, and Mount Lofty Botanic Garden.
name: Waterfall Gully

excerpt: Home to diverse native wildlife, this bushland area features hiking/walking trails & mountain views.
detail_description: Cleland National Park, located in the Adelaide Hills, offers a variety of hiking trails through bushland where visitors can spot diverse native wildlife. The park is known for its popular Waterfall Gully to Mount Lofty hike and a section of the Heysen Trail. In addition to these well-known routes, there are 11 other trails that provide opportunities to observe koalas, kangaroos, and birdlife while traversing dense bushland and challenging inclines.
name: Cleland National Park

excerpt: McLaren Vale is a town and locality in the Australian state of South Australia located about 33 kilometres south of the Adelaide city centre and about 9 kilometres south of the municipal seat at Noarlunga Centre. Wikipedia.
detail_description: McLaren Vale is a charming town and locality in South Australia, situated just 33 kilometers south of Adelaide. It's known for its proximity to other renowned wine regions like Barossa Valley and Clare Valley. The upcoming McLaren Vale Grenache & Gourmet event promises two weeks of fantastic experiences, making it an exciting destination for wine enthusiasts and foodies alike.
name: McLaren Vale

excerpt: Modern facility with interactive displays about winemaking, a tasting room & an event space.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Adelaide, the National Wine Centre of Australia is a captivating destination for anyone passionate about wine. This modern facility not only showcases the rich viticultural heritage of Australia but also offers interactive displays that delve into the art and science of winemaking. Visitors can explore various wine varieties through engaging exhibits, while tasting rooms provide an opportunity to savor exquisite wines from South Australia's renowned regions. The striking architecture, reminiscent of a giant barrel, adds to its charm and makes it a visual delight.
name: National Wine Centre of Australia
address: Corner of Hackney Rd &, Botanic Rd, SA 5000, Australia

excerpt: Landmark neo-Gothic Anglican cathedral operating since 1878 with notable stained glass & sculptures.
detail_description: St Peter's Cathedral, a stunning neo-Gothic Anglican cathedral in Adelaide, South Australia, has been an iconic landmark since 1878. The cathedral boasts remarkable stained glass windows and sculptures that captivate visitors. Its architecture is reminiscent of the Cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris, featuring a striking rose window depicting stories of South Australia and the Bible. Inside, the cathedral spans 203 feet with a serene Lady Chapel occupying 30 feet.
name: St Peter's Cathedral
address: 27 King William Rd, North Adelaide SA 5006, Australia

detail_description: North Terrace, located in Adelaide, is a cultural boulevard and a major tourist attraction. It houses the prestigious Art Gallery of South Australia, which boasts an extensive collection of over 38,000 artworks from various regions including Asia, North America, Europe, and Australia. The gallery showcases diverse art forms such as painting, photography, sculpture, metalworks and jewelry.
name: North Terrace

excerpt: Up-and-coming Henley Beach has a mellow, seaside feel and a vibrant food scene, with upscale seafood restaurants and cool Modern Australian eateries sharing space with fish and chip shops, long-established pubs and ice cream parlours. A long stretch of fine sand draws swimmers, paddleboarders and walkers, and the jetty is a popular fishing spot. Quirky shops sell beachwear, indie fashion and stylish homeware.
detail_description: Henley Beach is an up-and-coming coastal destination with a relaxed atmosphere and a diverse culinary scene. Visitors can enjoy upscale seafood restaurants, modern Australian eateries, as well as traditional fish and chip shops and charming ice cream parlors. The long sandy beach attracts swimmers, paddleboarders, and leisurely strollers while the jetty is a popular spot for fishing enthusiasts. Additionally, the area offers unique shopping opportunities with stores selling beachwear, indie fashion, and stylish homeware.
name: Henley Beach

excerpt: Port Adelaide is a rejuvenated industrial district, home to the South Australian Maritime Museum, South Australian Aviation Museum and National Railway Museum. Hart’s Mill hosts music and art events, plus a Sunday food market. Self-guided tours take in the Port Adelaide Lighthouse and other 1800s buildings and heritage pubs, along with galleries and the area's eclectic shops .
detail_description: Port Adelaide, a revitalized industrial area, is home to several museums including the South Australian Maritime Museum, South Australian Aviation Museum and National Railway Museum. Hart’s Mill hosts various cultural events and a Sunday food market. Visitors can explore the Port Adelaide Lighthouse and other 1800s buildings on self-guided tours. The area also features heritage pubs, galleries, and unique shops.
name: Port Adelaide

excerpt: Well-preserved 1930s estate turned museum featuring a notable art collection & formal gardens.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Adelaide, Carrick Hill is a beautifully preserved estate from the 1930s that has been transformed into a captivating museum. Visitors can explore its impressive art collection and wander through meticulously maintained formal gardens. The estate offers an enchanting experience for families, featuring the delightful Storybook Trail that invites children to engage with nature while discovering whimsical elements inspired by classic tales.
name: Carrick Hill House Museum & Garden
address: 46 Carrick Hill Dr, Springfield SA 5062, Australia

excerpt: Rugged reserve with walking tracks to several seasonal waterfalls, rock climbing & wildlife viewing.
detail_description: Morialta Conservation Park, located just a short distance from Adelaide CBD, offers a rugged and untapped wilderness experience with woodlands, gorges, and seasonal waterfalls. The park's history dates back to the 1800s when it was used for primary production activities. Today, visitors can explore hiking trails that lead to stunning cliffs and seasonal waterfalls such as Morialta Falls.
name: Morialta Conservation Park
address: Morialta Falls Rd, Woodforde SA 5072, Australia

excerpt: Major performing arts centre with spaces hosting a programme of music, theatre, dance & exhibitions.
detail_description: The Adelaide Festival Centre is a prominent performing arts hub in South Australia, offering a diverse program of music, theatre, dance, and exhibitions. It hosts renowned events such as the Adelaide Cabaret Festival, OzAsia Festival, DreamBIG Children's Festival, Adelaide Guitar Festival, and MOB. Known as 'Mad March,' the city comes alive with various cultural celebrations including the Adelaide Fringe and the Adelaide 500 motor-racing event.
name: Adelaide Festival Centre
address: King William Rd, Adelaide SA 5000, Australia

excerpt: Massive green space made up of more than 27 city parks, plus a botanical garden & playgrounds.
detail_description: Adelaide Parklands is a vast expanse of greenery, comprising over 27 city parks, a botanical garden, and various playgrounds. Encompassing 7,600,000 square meters of natural space, it offers diverse experiences for visitors. The Adelaide Himeji Gardens presents a traditional Japanese design as a gift from Adelaide's sister city. Additionally, the area features accessible play spaces for children and BMX tracks for thrill-seekers.
name: Adelaide Parklands

excerpt: Popular area for hiking & mountain biking, with a cafe, souvenir shop & viewing platform.
detail_description: Mount Lofty is a popular destination for outdoor enthusiasts, offering hiking and mountain biking trails in the Adelaide Hills. Visitors can also enjoy amenities such as a cafe, souvenir shop, and a viewing platform. The area is part of the picturesque landscape of Adelaide, situated between the Gulf St Vincent and the Mount Lofty Ranges. Nature lovers can explore nearby conservation parks and gardens to experience local flora and fauna. Additionally, rugby fans can visit the Adelaide Oval for guided tours.
name: Mount Lofty

detail_description: Semaphore Beach, located in Adelaide, South Australia, is a popular destination known for its historical significance and rich cultural heritage. Bordered by sand dunes, this wide and long beach offers expansive foreshore and boulevard adorned with Art Deco buildings reminiscent of the grandeur of the Palais. Visitors can enjoy classic gourmet dining and a fine selection of wines while taking in the picturesque coastline.
name: Semaphore Beach

excerpt: Ticketed wine-tasting sessions focusing on a particular grape or vintage from the adjoining estate.
detail_description: Penfolds Magill Estate Cellar Door, nestled in Adelaide's foothills, is the birthplace of Australia's renowned Penfolds Grange wine. Established in 1844 by English doctor Christopher Rawson Penfold, this historic winery offers a range of wine-tasting experiences and tours. Visitors can explore the underground tunnels and bluestone cellars, visit the Grange Cottage and vintage cellar, and enjoy structured tastings of Penfolds' highly-coveted wines.
name: Penfolds Magill Estate Cellar Door

excerpt: Permanent collections & temporary exhibits on nautical history, plus an 1869 lighthouse.
detail_description: The South Australian Maritime Museum, situated in Port Adelaide just a short drive from central Adelaide, offers an immersive experience into maritime history. Housed in a restored stone warehouse, the museum features permanent collections and temporary exhibits that showcase nautical history through ships' figureheads, shipwreck relics, and intricate scale models including a walkable ketch. Visitors can explore the basement to see a bunk bed aboard an 1840s immigrant ship and learn about the challenging journeys to South Australia.
name: South Australian Maritime Museum
address: 126 Lipson St, Port Adelaide SA 5015, Australia

excerpt: Animal park where guests can hold koalas & view Australian & exotic mammals, birds & reptiles.
detail_description: Gorge Wildlife Park, nestled in the scenic Adelaide Hills and just a short drive from Adelaide, offers an exceptional opportunity to interact closely with a diverse array of Australian and exotic wildlife. Established in 1965 and spanning 14 acres of natural bushland, this family-operated sanctuary is home to koalas, kangaroos, wombats, dingoes, alligators, as well as various birds and reptiles. Visitors can hold koalas and observe these animals up close.
name: Gorge Wildlife Park
address: 30 Redden Dr, Cudlee Creek SA 5232, Australia

detail_description: Mount Lofty Summit, located just a short drive from Crafers township, is the highest peak in Adelaide. It offers breathtaking panoramic views of the city skyline and surrounding hills. Visitors can also enjoy The Summit Restaurant and Cafe, a Visitor Information Outlet, and a gift shop at the summit.
name: Mount Lofty Summit
address: Mount Lofty Summit Rd, Crafers SA 5152, Australia

excerpt: Hiking & mountain biking in wild bushland home to koalas & kangaroos, plus sports grounds.
detail_description: Belair National Park, located just 25 minutes south-east of Adelaide CBD, offers a variety of activities for visitors. It is the birthplace of South Australia's national parks system and has a rich history dating back to 1837. The park features hiking and mountain biking trails, as well as sports grounds including tennis courts and cricket pitches. Additionally, it is home to koalas and kangaroos in its wild bushland.
name: Belair National Park
address: Upper Sturt Rd, Belair SA 5052, Australia

detail_description: Nestled in the Adelaide Hills, Mount Lofty House offers a stately and luxurious retreat. Guests can enjoy stunning views of Piccadilly Valley from the balcony while savoring a delicious breakfast featuring high-quality ingredients. The hotel's warm hospitality and efficient service create a welcoming atmosphere, making guests feel right at home. With spacious and comfortable rooms, it's an ideal choice for a relaxing getaway or even a wedding celebration.
name: Mount Lofty House

detail_description: MOD PIZZERIA is located in a historic 1920s building at Rundle Mall, offering mod-minimalist rooms with luxurious amenities. The pizzeria is known for its delicious and generous pizzas with fresh toppings that don't leave you feeling heavy after the meal. Customers appreciate the accommodating owners who are open to adding extra toppings. The restaurant also offers a variety of vegetarian options, including flavorful paneer pizzas.
name: Mod Pizzeria
address: Shop 1/952 North East Road, Modbury SA 5092, Australia

excerpt: 1931 monument commemorating South Australian World War I casualties, including a list of the fallen.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Adelaide, the National War Memorial stands as a poignant reminder of the sacrifices made by South Australians during World War I. Opened in 1931, this striking monument is crafted from Harcourt granite and Macclesfield marble, featuring intricate sculptures by renowned artist George Rayner Hoff. His work captures the profound emotions felt by soldiers and their families amidst conflict.
name: National War Memorial

excerpt: 97-acre, sloping gardens with a lake, extensive walking trails & themed gullies with exotic plants.
detail_description: Nestled between Crafers and Piccadilly, Mount Lofty Botanic Garden spans 97 acres of sloping terrain, featuring a picturesque lake, extensive walking trails, and themed gullies adorned with exotic plants. The garden showcases a diverse array of flora from various regions including South America, China, East Africa, New Zealand, South East Asia, North America as well as Australian natives.
name: Mount Lofty Botanic Garden

excerpt: Indoor-outdoor museum featuring steam engines, carriages, train rides, a model railroad & more.
detail_description: The National Railway Museum in Port Adelaide is a must-visit for both train enthusiasts and families. It boasts an extensive collection of steam engines, carriages, and other railway memorabilia. Visitors can explore numerous fascinating exhibits and even take a ride on an old train for a small additional fee. The museum features over 100 exhibits representing various railway operators across Australia's major rail gauges.
name: National Railway Museum
address: 76 Lipson St, Port Adelaide SA 5015, Australia

excerpt: West Beach is a laid-back suburb with an uncrowded, family-friendly stretch of sand that's popular for swimming, kitesurfing and paddleboarding. Steps from the beach, the Mega Adventure park has aerial obstacle courses. Harbour Town outlet centre has global fashion at reduced prices, and ice cream parlours and relaxed eateries dot the area. The River Torrens Linear Trail leads from the seafront to the city centre.
detail_description: West Beach is a relaxed coastal suburb featuring a spacious and family-friendly beach perfect for various water activities like swimming, kitesurfing, and paddleboarding. The area also offers the Mega Adventure park with thrilling aerial obstacle courses and the Harbour Town outlet center for discounted global fashion. Additionally, visitors can enjoy ice cream parlors and casual dining options nearby. For those interested in exploring nature, the River Torrens Linear Trail provides a scenic route from the seafront to the city center.
name: West Beach

excerpt: Compact Chinatown with bubble-tea shops, grocery stores & restaurants serving potsticker dumplings.
detail_description: Chinatown Adelaide South, located at the south-east end of Adelaide's CBD, is a vibrant and internationally famous area known for its diverse culinary offerings. This compact district features bubble-tea shops, grocery stores, and restaurants serving potsticker dumplings. The main street is adorned with two large Paifang marking the entrances at either end, stretching from Grote Street to Gouger Street.
name: Chinatown Adelaide South Australia

excerpt: Grand 19th-century manor offering Victorian-era decor & antiques, plus tours & family activities.
detail_description: Ayers House Museum, located just outside the C.B.D. of Adelaide, is a grand 19th-century manor that showcases Victorian-era decor and antiques. Originally built in 1846, it was transformed into an elegant 40-room mansion by Henry Ayers, a prominent politician of South Australia. The museum offers guided tours and family activities on weekends, allowing visitors to explore three levels filled with beautiful architecture and well-maintained Victorian-era furnishings.
name: Ayers House Museum

detail_description: The Adelaide Fringe Festival is a vibrant and eclectic celebration of art and culture, taking place from February to March in the heart of Adelaide City. As one of the oldest and biggest arts festivals in the Southern Hemisphere, it offers a diverse range of events including circus, theatre, cabaret, comedy, music, workshops, and visual arts. With something for everyone to enjoy during its 31-day run, visitors can expect a transformation of the city into an explosion of creativity.
name: Adelaide Fringe

detail_description: JamFactory, a renowned institution in Adelaide's arts scene for over four decades, is situated in a purpose-built facility within the West End arts precinct. It serves as a hub for creatives and art enthusiasts alike. The not-for-profit organization supports local artists, craftspeople, and designers through its four gallery spaces and fully equipped studios for ceramics, glass, furniture, and metalwork. Visitors can explore the latest exhibitions while shopping at the flagship retail store offering handcrafted jewelry and unique homewares.
name: JamFactory

excerpt: Multi-hangar museum with historic planes, including an F-111 bomber, & other related artifacts.
detail_description: The South Australian Aviation Museum, located in Port Adelaide, is a multi-hangar museum that showcases a diverse collection of historic planes and aviation artifacts. Housed in a WWII hangar, the museum features approximately 15 aircraft including an impressive F-111 bomber. Visitors can explore themed galleries filled with modern and heritage aircraft, engines, propellers, and rockets. Guided tours are available for those interested in delving deeper into the history of specific planes.
name: South Australian Aviation Museum
address: 16 Bedford St, Port Adelaide SA 5015, Australia

excerpt:
Maslin Beach is a southern coastal suburb of Adelaide, South Australia. It is located in the City of Onkaparinga.
The name refers to the town of Maslin Beach, the beach after which it was named and the suburb which contains both. In this article, the name refers to the suburb, unless stated otherwise. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Maslin Beach is a charming coastal suburb situated in the southern part of Adelaide, South Australia. It falls under the City of Onkaparinga and is known for its picturesque beach that shares its name with the town. The suburb encompasses various other neighboring areas like McLaren Vale, Moana, and Port Noarlunga. With its beautiful coastline and proximity to several scenic locales, Maslin Beach offers visitors a delightful blend of natural beauty and coastal charm.
name: Maslin Beach

excerpt: Sprawling complex featuring stores offering sale-priced merchandise from popular labels.
detail_description: Harbour Town Premium Outlets Adelaide is a sprawling shopping complex that houses over 130 well-known Australian and international brands, offering sale-priced merchandise. The outlet center features national and international brands with discounts ranging from 30 to 70 percent below the suggested retail price. It offers a wide variety of shopping options, including fashion, accessories, homeware, and more.
name: Harbour Town Premium Outlets Adelaide
address: 727 Tapleys Hill Rd, Adelaide Airport SA 5950, Australia

excerpt: Expansive, industrial-style venue with more than 20 beers on tap, plus pub grub & outdoor space.
detail_description: Pirate Life Brewing is a renowned craft brewery in Adelaide that has made its mark on the city's craft beer scene. Founded by brewer mates Jack Cameron and Jared Red Proudfoot, the brewery offers an expansive industrial-style venue with over 20 beers on tap, along with pub grub and outdoor space. The brewery has come a long way from its origins in a rental property's shed in the Barossa Valley to its current large warehouse in Royal Park.
name: Pirate Life Brewing
address: 18 Baker St, Port Adelaide SA 5015, Australia
